761. caespite. So Caesar says c. 96 ‘in castris Pompei uidere licuit trichilas stratas, magnum argenti pondus expositum, recentibus caespitibus tabernacula constrata, L. etiam Lentuli et nonnullorum taber· nacula protecta hedera.’ Plut. Pomp. 72, describing the same scene of luxury, says πᾶσα ’γὰρ σκηνὴ μυρσίναις κατέστεπτο καὶ στρωμναῖς ἀνθιναῖς ἤσκητο καὶ τραπέζαις ἐκπωμάτων μεσταῖς. Lucan, it will be observed, mentions only the sods of turf. No doubt the plate and other appliances were bellorum in sumptus (753). caesum (Crit. App), the regular word for hewing wood, turf, or stone: cf. Caesar B. G. 5. 42 ‘gladiis caespites circumcidere? It is here applied to the cubile made out of the sods.
